findings.recommendation:
Replace the string-replacement approach with a proper POSIX-flag tokeniser. Split the raw command on ASCII whitespace (not a single space), discard tokens that are pure flag strings (match regex ^-[a-zA-Z]+$), and collect the remaining tokens as paths. Then check each path against the block-list. Example:

```rust
fn extract_rm_paths(cmd: &str) -> Vec<String> {
    let tokens: Vec<&str> = cmd.split_ascii_whitespace().collect();
    // skip 'rm' itself and any pure-flag tokens
    tokens.iter().skip(1)
        .filter(|t| !t.starts_with('-'))
        .map(|t| t.trim_matches(|c| c == '\"' || c == '\'')
        .to_string())
        .collect()
}

const CRITICAL_PATHS: &[&str] = &["/", "~", "/*", "~/", "~/*"];

if tokens[0] == "rm" && has_recursive_flag(&tokens) {
    for path in extract_rm_paths(cmd) {
        if CRITICAL_PATHS.contains(&path.as_str()) {
            return Some(format!("rm -rf on critical path: {path}"));
        }
    }
}
```
Also normalise env-vars: reject any path that starts with '$' or contains shell metacharacters (';', '&&', '||', '|', '`').

